Benetton willingly took the risk of being hated on scale and this is what sets them apart from the mainstream clutter.

After all, the ‘United’ in UCB stands true to its meaning — uniting everyone across all the spectrums of gender, creed and color for a just cause.

To say that Benetton used shock value just to sell their products would be an understatement. 

No brand is able to carry ideas across the cultures better than Benetton does, demonstrating the ability of opening debates, raising attention to the issues that are otherwise ignored.

9. F/W 2011, “UNHATE”

Benetton’s new ad invited leaders and citizens of the world to combat the “culture of hatred”.

The ad featuring Pope and Imam garnered such extreme criticism that it had to be pulled out within a few hours of the launch. https://t.co/ninFvDoUPj

(contd.)

The ad created a storm & the state of Missouri decided to sue Benetton as the brand had deceived the state by using the death row inmates without the permission.

The boycott led by retail co. Sears cost the company millions of dollars in the revenue loss.

8. S/S 2000, “Looking death in the face”

The right to life shall be guaranteed to all. The brand, believing in its philosophy took a pro-life stance, casting 26 inmates from different U.S. states. 

The campaign took two years to finish and cost Benetton $10 million. (contd.) https://t.co/crPsix97RQ

7. S/S 1994, “Bosnian Soldier”

The ad shows the uniform of a fallen Bosnian soldier during the Bosnian war of 1992–95.

Many activists attacked the ad & deemed it insensitive. The ad created a huge cry in Croatia, which blamed Benetton for not respecting its national integrity.

6. F/W 1993, “HIV — Positive”

Benetton strived to start a conversation around the stigma but it backfired.
 
The company was fined for $32,000 by the French court who labelled the campaign intrusive and exploitive for using offensive imagery that further stigmatize HIV+ people. https://t.co/auTiSbF1KF

5. S/S 1992, “Murder”

In 1982, a photographer named Franco Zecchi captured the killing of an Italian mafia. 

Ten years later, Benetton featured the image in its campaign. As expected, the visual flared up the controversy and many publications refused to run the ad. https://t.co/dJ52Uhct5N

4. S/S 1992, “AIDS — David Kirby”

At the time of its release, the discourse on AIDS was still a taboo. 

Benetton was accused of using a man’s suffering as a commodity to sell their products.

Many gay rights activists in Europe took to the streets calling for the brand boycott. https://t.co/5V6PX2wOzp

3. F/W 1991, “Priest and Nun”

In Italy, bowing to the pressure from the Vatican and the public, this ad was finally banned. 

The French authorities also demanded the withdrawal of the posters. The offense was such that one-third of the magazines refused to run the ad. https://t.co/voaK5FXH0r

2. F/W 1991, “Newborn Baby”

Intended as an “anthem to life”, this campaign celebrates life through the imagery of life’s violent beginning.

The ad sparked protests in Italy where the authorities took the ads down. Magazines like Cosmopolitan & Elle also refused to run the ad. https://t.co/PCt6TFOmyc

1. F/W 1990, “Blanket”

The campaign was a real head-turner as its an unconventional portrayal of a family. 

The message of racial equality is clear, while also signaling that the brand embraces homosexuality. In addition to this comes the adopted child of a different ethnicity. https://t.co/EorvUxpx6x

In 1982, Oliviero Tuscani joined Benetton as a Creative Director. 

The campaigns that came under his visionary leadership were path-breaking, not only because of their provoking imagery, but also for the fact that Benetton pioneered the concept of product-less advertising.

In a world full of cookie-cutter advertisements, Benetton campaigns always stood out from the rest.

While some ads were banned outright, others went ahead to bag prestigious awards and recognitions.

At least in India, preservation of such structures is a far cry.

For the new age architecture enthusiasts these are Instagram-worthy #monuments. 

But for many, these structures embody the bureaucratic incompetence and red tapism of the pre-liberalized Indian economy.

(12/n)

These remnants of the socialist era now stand in the stark contrast with the contemporary urban architecture of the country.

Sure we need swanky malls, world class airports and convention centers. 

But do we really need to wipe out our past to achieve that?

(11/n)

INDIAN NATIONAL SCIENCE ACADEMY | #RajRewal (1990)

The ‘X’ shaped structure signifies progressive and bold image.

Built in 62,000 sq. m. in Delhi, the lower floors with large spans accommodate an auditorium and above floors with smaller spans provide for meeting rooms. https://t.co/ixPx6nW5po

(10/n)

CHANDIGARH CAPITOL COMPLEX | #LeCorbusier (1961)

Designated as #UNESCOWorldHeritage, any discourse about Brutalism is incomplete without its mention. 

The building was central to the new capital being designed for Punjab, as Lahore was given to Pakistan after partition. https://t.co/sDvwCaITCL

(9/n)

POLISH EMBASSY | #WitoldCeckiewicz (1973)

In the 60s, India and #Poland’s diplomatic ties were at all time high, as they shared similar #socialist economic model of development. 

A symbol of 'socialist #modernism', this structure in New Delhi is a result of those ties. https://t.co/kynBkHAmUa

(8/n)

PALIKA KENDRA | #KuldipSingh (1983)

Serving as NDMC HQ, this is another most celebrated work by Kuldip Singh. 

The building freely express the spirit of Brutalism — geometric structures with the use of concrete, which was a fairly modern design for India back then. https://t.co/fNQSZRvPAu

(7/n)

NDDB | #AchyutKanvinde (1985)

This masterpiece in Safdurjung, Delhi is Kanvinde's tribute to the true quintessential Brutalist aesthetic.

Though his intent was not to form India’s own Brutalist style but to develop a modern design through his functionalist approach. https://t.co/cLoJnsBfM6

(6/n)

SHRI RAM CENTRE | #ShivnathPrasad (1969)

A renowned theatre located at #MandiHouse, it is designed in a way to allow close interaction between audience and stage.

Without a doubt, it has been a center stage among many known #Bollywood and theatre personalities. https://t.co/UUJUhWktVz

(5/n)

NCDC | #KuldipSingh (1980)

Commonly popular as "pyjama building", the #NCDC building is an iconic landmark located in Hauz Khas, Delhi.

Two separate 9-story structures that meet at the top and stand as a fine example of making of a modernist city with limited resources. https://t.co/Mgw6jvZ6Wg

(4/n)

HALL OF NATIONS | #RajRewal (1972)

Once an icon to #Delhi’s skyline, this large spatial structure showed India’s confidence in hosting large-scale exhibitions. 

It blended the history with the modern ambitions of India which reflects itself in its name — #PragatiMaidan. https://t.co/8j0xRbIs69

(3/n)

Brutalism arrived in newly-independent India, then led by #JawaharLalNehru — an ardent believer of Fabian Socialism. Unlike today’s privatized and PPP models of development, the economy of that era was heavily controlled by the state.

Some of the finest structures here👇 https://t.co/k2hPRg65Go

(2/n)

#Brutalism arrived from post-war Europe. It is characterized by its geometry, rawness and unabashed use of concrete; which was convenient, inexpensive and readily available at the time.

Loved by some, loathed by many; it is the most polarizing style of #architecture.

(1/n)

Theatres, institutions, exhibition centers and more. Most of you must've seen these #Brutalist architecture marvels across Delhi and elsewhere. 

This is how #Brutalism became a symbol of India's post-colonial ambitions.
